'''David Henry Frisch''' (March 12, 1918 – May 23, 1991) was an American [[physicist]] who helped develop the [[atom bomb]] in [[World War II]] and later became active in the [[nuclear disarmament|disarmament]] movement.<ref>{{cite journal|author=[[Victor Weisskopf|Weisskopf, Victor]]; [[Francis E. Low|Low, Francis]]; Osborne, Louis|title=Obituary: David H. Frisch|journal=Physics Today|date=July 1992|volume=45|issue=7|pages=80–81|url=http://www.physicstoday.org/resource/1/phtoad/v45/i7/p80_s2?bypassSSO=1|doi=10.1063/1.2809748|bibcode=1992PhT....45g..80W|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131004225113/http://www.physicstoday.org/resource/1/phtoad/v45/i7/p80_s2?bypassSSO=1|archivedate=2013-10-04|df=}}</ref> He was also the husband of [[Rose Frisch|Rose Epstein Frisch]].
==Biography== Born in [[New York, New York|New York]], Frisch grew up in [[San Antonio]] and graduated from [[Princeton University|Princeton]] in 1940. He was a [[graduate assistant]] at the [[University of Wisconsin–Madison]] from 1940 to 1942, and then worked at [[Los Alamos National Laboratory|Los Alamos]] from 1943 to 1945. After the war he moved to [[MIT]], beginning as a research associate in 1946, obtained his PhD in 1947 and was appointed an assistant professor in 1948, associate professor in 1952 and full professor in 1958. He retired in 1988.
Frisch was a fellow of the [[American Physical Society]] and of the [[American Academy of Arts and Sciences]]. He was the recipient of [[Fulbright Program|Fulbright]], [[Guggenheim Fellowship|Guggenheim]], [[Alfred P. Sloan]] and National Science Foundation research fellowships.
Frisch served on the Physics Advisory Committee of the [[National Science Foundation]], on the [[Brookhaven National Laboratory|Brookhaven]] High Energy Advisory Committee, and was chairman of the Long-Range Planning committee of the [[Fermi National Accelerator Laboratory]].
Frisch was active in the field of nuclear disarmament, participating in the [[Pugwash Conferences on Science and World Affairs|Moscow Pugwash Conference]] in 1960, editing the book ''Arms Reduction'' in 1961, and participating in the 1962 Woods Hole Summer Study on Inspection.
Among his scientific publications was a 1963 paper in which he and [[James H. Smith (physicist)|James H. Smith]] succeeded in showing objective [[time dilation]] in the decay of cosmic [[muons]]. A thirty-five-minute movie describing this experiment performed both on the top of [[Mount Washington (New Hampshire)|Mount Washington]] in [[New Hampshire]] as well as at [[MIT]] is available online.<ref>http://www.scivee.tv/node/2415</ref>
He was married to biologist [[Rose Epstein Frisch|Rose Frisch]].
==Selected publications== *D.H. Frisch and J.H. Smith, Am. J. Phys., 31, 342-355 (1963).
